t_agentic_code"},{"short_id":"mlm7ne","created_at":"2026-05-30T02:17:22.000-05:00","title":"The Critical State of Cyberspace","url":"https://www.jstor.org/content/pdf/oa_chapter_edited/jj.40494811.19?acceptTC=true\u0026coverpage=false\u0026addFooter=false","score":2,"flags":0,"comment_count":2,"description":"\u003cp\u003eNATO is currently in a ‘grey zone’: increasingly being challenged in cyberspace while unable to attribute attacks, thus failing to deter. Simultaneously, many governments, businesses, and populations depend on the Internet and the cloud to function properly. This is a dangerous situation, since global Internet connectivity could get disrupted and destabilised. This chapter explains the basic principles from an overall technological perspective, and discusses the challenge of anti-access and area denial (A2/AD) in the context of global Internet disruptions. What is the contested area, what are possible effects, and can those effects be limited? Using a layered approach, we define the cyber ‘high ground’ as maintenance of and control over critical infrastructure, from core to edge, from hardware to software. To ensure each cyber ‘area’ can be protected in isolation but still allow global cooperation, we argue it is important to control which paths data takes in the network, similar to air traffic control. This requires a new approach to organisation: we discuss a decentralised architecture for cyberspace, and how the Internet can be structured using federated networks, featuring geofencing and effect isolation, that has the potential to radically change the future of cyber warfare.\u003c/p\u003e\n","description_plain":"NATO is currently in a ‘grey zone’: increasingly being challenged in cyberspace while unable to attribute attacks, thus failing to deter. Simultaneously, many governments, businesses, and populations depend on the Internet and the cloud to function properly. This is a dangerous situation, since global Internet connectivity could get disrupted and destabilised. This chapter explains the basic principles from an overall technological perspective, and discusses the challenge of anti-access and area denial (A2/AD) in the context of global Internet disruptions. What is the contested area, what are possible effects, and can those effects be limited? Using a layered approach, we define the cyber ‘high ground’ as maintenance of and control over critical infrastructure, from core to edge, from hardware to software. To ensure each cyber ‘area’ can be protected in isolation but still allow global cooperation, we argue it is important to control which paths data takes in the network, similar to air traffic control. This requires a new approach to organisation: we discuss a decentralised architecture for cyberspace, and how the Internet can be structured using federated networks, featuring geofencing and effect isolation, that has the potential to radically change the future of cyber warfare.","submitter_user":"praalhans","user_is_author":true,"tags":["pdf","science"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/mlm7ne","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/mlm7ne/critical_state_cyberspace"},{"short_id":"sgbvmj","created_at":"2026-05-30T01:00:19.000-05:00","title":"OpenRCT2 v0.5.1 “Swamp Castle\" released! Last version to support Windows 7","url":"https://openrct2.io/blog/2026/05/openrct2-v0.5.1-released","score":4,"flags":0,"comment_count":2,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"raymii","user_is_author":false,"tags":["c++","games","release"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/sgbvmj","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/sgbvmj/openrct2_v0_5_1_swamp_castle_released_last"},{"short_id":"vdojf3","created_at":"2026-05-29T10:29:40.000-05:00","title":"NNN Stack: NixOS, Niri, Noctalia","url":"https://the-nnn-stack.github.io","score":14,"flags":3,"comment_count":8,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"dhofer","user_is_author":false,"tags":["linux","nix"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/vdojf3","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/vdojf3/nnn_stack_nixos_niri_noctalia"},{"short_id":"7lrk2t","created_at":"2026-05-29T04:18:06.000-05:00","title":"Leaving performance on the table","url":"https://fzakaria.com/2026/05/23/leaving-performance-on-the-table","score":30,"flags":0,"comment_count":4,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"confusedalex","user_is_author":false,"tags":["compilers","performance"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/7lrk2t","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/7lrk2t/leaving_performance_on_table"},{"short_id":"1fkt8w","created_at":"2026-05-29T00:58:06.000-05:00","title":"Patching my guitar amp's firmware","url":"https://mforney.org/blog/2026-05-28-patching-my-guitar-amps-firmware.html","score":31,"flags":0,"comment_count":4,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"mcf","user_is_author":true,"tags":["hardware","reversing"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/1fkt8w","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/1fkt8w/patching_my_guitar_amp_s_firmware"},{"short_id":"g9u6b7","created_at":"2026-05-29T00:44:56.000-05:00","title":"How do you version public web APIs?","url":"","score":31,"flags":0,"comment_count":9,"description":"\u003cp\u003eOften there is an existing API called something like \"Product API\". It often also has /api/v1 in the path.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eTo me this often feels like an antipattern, especially when the API itself uses semantic versioning: mixing the routes with the API contract.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eHaving /v1/ in the URL while also having a major.minor.patch version: coupling the first number of the semantic version to the URL path feels counter intuitive to me, if you make a breaking change, you may need new paths and new reverse proxy routes, and whatnot, and you also spread the API contract to two places, the URL and the version number.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eIf you start simultaneously building a brand new successor to the \"Product API\", the old API is effectively stuck as \"v1\", even if it gets breaking changes of its own.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eWhat do you think?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eDo you have any API design pet peeves or opinions to share?\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eSorry for the confusing brain dump text, very interested in hearing people's opinions.\u003c/p\u003e\n\u003cp\u003eThank you\u003c/p\u003e\n","description_plain":"Often there is an existing API called something like \"Product API\". It often also has /api/v1 in the path.\r\n\r\nTo me this often feels like an antipattern, especially when the API itself uses semantic versioning: mixing the routes with the API contract.\r\n\r\nHaving /v1/ in the URL while also having a major.minor.patch version: coupling the first number of the semantic version to the URL path feels counter intuitive to me, if you make a breaking change, you may need new paths and new reverse proxy routes, and whatnot, and you also spread the API contract to two places, the URL and the version number.\r\n\r\nIf you start simultaneously building a brand new successor to the \"Product API\", the old API is effectively stuck as \"v1\", even if it gets breaking changes of its own.\r\n\r\nWhat do you think?\r\n\r\nDo you have any API design pet peeves or opinions to share?\r\n\r\nSorry for the confusing brain dump text, very interested in hearing people's opinions.\r\n\r\nThank you","submitter_user":"jussi","user_is_author":true,"tags":["api","ask"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/g9u6b7","comments_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/g9u6b7/how_do_you_version_public_web_apis"},{"short_id":"brusu8","created_at":"2026-05-28T13:17:31.000-05:00","title":"Protestware for coding agents","url":"https://nesbitt.io/2026/05/28/protestware-for-coding-agents.html","score":103,"flags":0,"comment_count":103,"description":"","description_plain":"","submitter_user":"bitshift","user_is_author":false,"tags":["security","vibecoding"],"short_id_url":"https://lobste.rs/s/brusu8","comments_url":"https://lobst